# Convex Queries in Hooks

Do not call `convexQuery` (or Convex query APIs) directly inside components. Extract query usage into custom hooks under `src/hooks/queries/`. The hook should return only the data the UI needs (e.g. the user), not the full query result. That way components stay testable: you only mock the returned value (e.g. a user object).

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – query in component
export function SubscriptionPage() {
  const { data: user } = useSuspenseQuery(convexQuery(api.users.getCurrentUser, {}));
  // ...
}
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – hook re-exports query result (component must mock { data, isLoading, ... })
export function useCurrentUser() {
  return useSuspenseQuery(convexQuery(api.users.getCurrentUser, {}));
}
```

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD – hook returns only what we use (component mocks user)
export function useCurrentUser() {
  const { data } = useSuspenseQuery(convexQuery(api.users.getCurrentUser, {}));
  return data;
}
```

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD – component gets the value directly
export function SubscriptionPage() {
  const user = useCurrentUser();
  // ...
}
```

- One query (or related set) per hook file under `src/hooks/queries/`.
- Return the data the UI needs (user, list, etc.), not the query result object.
- Name hooks after the data they expose (e.g. `useCurrentUser`, `useLists`).
